  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>NJOY & Smokeless Success:</strong> If Altria captures significant market share in the rapidly growing e-vapor market via its NJOY acquisition, or oral nicotine (on!), long-term volume declines could reverse.</li>
    <li><strong>Share buybacks:</strong> The model holds shares constant. Altria frequently buys back stock, which would artificially boost intrinsic value per share over time.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory clarity:</strong> A favorable FDA ruling on next-generation products or a loosening of PMTA (Premarket Tobacco Product Application) restrictions.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Accelerated volume declines:</strong> If smoking cessation trends steepen or illicit disposable vapes severely cannibalize cigarette sales faster than Altria can raise prices.</li>
    <li><strong>Menthol ban:</strong> The FDA's ongoing pursuit of a nationwide menthol cigarette ban would heavily impact Altria's core portfolio.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt burden:</strong> Altria holds substantial long-term debt ($25.7B). In a higher-for-longer interest rate environment, refinancing this debt will increase interest expenses, directly reducing Free Cash Flow.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of Dividend Discount Model (DDM) for MO?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While the Dividend Discount Model is excellent for companies like Altria that return most cash to shareholders, a DCF captures the total free cash flow generation capacity of the business, regardless of whether management chooses to pay it out, buy back shares, or pay down debt. FCF gives the most accurate picture of baseline enterprise value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why 8.5% discount rate instead of the typical 10%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Altria has deeply entrenched brand loyalty (Marlboro) and an inelastic product, providing cash flow stability that merits a slightly lower discount rate than high-growth or cyclical tech stocks. Its historically low beta (~0.7) supports a cost of equity in the 8% range, but we bump it to 8.5% to account for sector-specific regulatory risks.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is 0% terminal growth realistic?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">For a tobacco company, yes. Assuming positive perpetual growth implies cigarettes will be sold in increasing volumes (or exponentially increasing prices) until the end of time. 0% is a conservative middle ground: it assumes that while volume declines, price hikes and smokeless transitions will keep the absolute cash dollar amount perfectly flat indefinitely.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value based on specific assumptions. Altria has a high dividend yield which forms a significant part of its total return profile. You must conduct your own due diligence and consider your personal portfolio strategy.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

